	   <tr><td colspan=2>Hey.<br><br>I can reply to this one, 'cos it's small and I haven't gotta collect loads of time to reply.  *Grin*  I <b>will</b> reply to the epic rant eventually.<br><br><LI><b>PvP servers:</b><br>I think maybe you missed something.  The PvP servers aren't under populated because of balancing.  Consider how many people play EQ.  Now think about the percentage of them that actually want to play PvP.  (Not a whole lot, is it?)  EQ isn't really a PvP game at all.  The very structure of it, works against it being PvP.  <i>(Do you really wanna spend ages building a character and questing for an item to have it looted, because you died?  I sure as Hell don't.  I have enough trouble getting nice stuff as it is.)</i>  I think you'll find this is why PvP servers are underpopulated.  <br>NB:  I know a large number of people who play PvP.  Invariably, they play the PvP servers as light relief and spend most of their time in PvE servers.  I think this supports my argument.<br><br><LI><b>Roleplay servers:</b><br>A similar thing here.  Roleplay is restrictive.  I used to play a text MUD, which went from being open to having enforced RP rules!  This killed it for me and for everyone I knew who played there.  <br>On the other hand, there is nothing that stops anyone roleplaying on normal servers.  Just as with the PvP issue, the thing here is that people don't want to roleplay.  (I surely don't!  I'm quite happy as it is.  <i>(Mostly.)</i>)<br>Additionally, you should consider the economy of the FV server.  It is a newer and underpopulated server.  As much as people complain about the economy of EQ, it has benefits.  On a new server, there will be fewer people with high tradeskills.  Thus the cost of the items they make will be higher.  If you have a friend who plays on FV and you want his helps, it's gonna be a while, before he can twink you, innit?  (Like it or not, this <b>IS</b> reality!)<br><i>(How long do you think it will be before anyone raids ToV on the FV server???)</i><br><br><LI><b>'Same ol', same ol':</b><br>One other issue.  It's all the same.  Herein lies the rub.  You have to remember, that this is what people want, for the most part.  <i>"If it ain't broken, don't fix it!"</i>  EQ isn't broken.  (Hush now, wait a moment!)  Think of EQ as a business.  That's what it is.  Nothing more, nothing less.  The important thing here is profit Vs. cost.  Do you suppose Verant/Sony are making more, or less from EQ than other comparable game developers?<br>You know the answer to this as well as I do.  They're raking money in hand over fist.  This indicates that it is a good product.  (<i>"Quality is the sum of all features and aspects that define how well a product fulfills it's requirements."</i>  I murdered that quote, but this is part of the ISO9001 regulations.  What is the purpose of EQ?  (Think carefully now.)  It is to make money.  Does it do that?  Oh, my word, yes it does!)  It ain't broken and it ain't gonna get fixed.<br>This of course, runs into your complaints about cheesy tactics.  (I will deal with that another time.)  The fact of the matter is, the quality of a tactic is defined purely by how well it works.  If it works, it doesn't matter how poorly considered, planned, or enacted it was.  <br><br>Anyhow, I have to run.  Talk to ya later.<br><br>AlAaraaf.<br><br><br><br>&nbsp;<br>"Te aurdire no possum. Musa sapienum fixa est in aura."</td></tr>
