	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.45]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Hi, I am sure you have noticed a name change, well I changed it to reflect the point of this journal, to rant on video games in general. Well, my week was not so good considering my girlfriend effectively dumped me today, but I will not rant on that but on something I wanted to talk about for a long time, the lack of creativity in the gaming industry. So here is the rant(Btw these are now written in word then pasted in, so they should be edited better):<br><br>A few years ago I read a rant on ign.com(I am sure its still archived there, check n64.ign.com) about how video games get made from a creative standpoint. Most gaming ideas fall into three categories: genre, licenses and franchises.  Genres are like RPGs or FPS or if you want to get specific, Resident evil style survival horror games. Licences are self-explanatory, they are games based on movies, sports ect. Finally, franchises are like Mario or Final Fantasy games, games that star the same characters or in FF’s case, are in a series that share similar characteristics. The essay also went on to say that gaming companies, like things that are known to succeed, that why those most games fall into those 3 categories.  Though the article can get a little over the edge, it all true.<br><br>Readers, lets face it, we like different and do not like to play the same old thing except for *cough* DAOC*cough*. However, gaming company’s keep throwing out the same old crap that is just like every other platformer you’ve played; except for the rare instance in which creativity is used. However those creative games are either A) not marketed, or B) so popular its get copied a thousand times by competitors and so the ideas involved end up becoming generic. Licensed games are even worse than genres because with a few notable exceptions (you know who you are) they SUCK.  Franchises can be just as bad too. If it is Final Fantasy or Zelda, then its cool because they are examples of GOOD franchises; but what “Army Men” game do you remember that was good. Head Games kept releasing “extreme” sports games(extreme paintbrawl was the only game to get below a one at Ignpc) that were horrible until they wised up.   <br><br>I am tired of all the crap, so gamers I ask: How many resident evil clones are there? How many times have we seem get the 120 stars except this time it’s a token in the place of a star? How many NFL games can you play?  Has there been many good games based on movies other than Goldeneye and Aliens 3 for the Snes(this got on Nintendo power’s top 100 list of the greatest games of all time and when I played it, it was decent)?<br> The answers to these questions are obvious. <br><br>But wait, the gaming companies have marketing research on their side. They know people are buying these crappy games because they are sheep. So proud readers, educate your fellow consumers on how to buy smart (read “how not to buy a game,” for some tips to smart game buying) and tell the vampires that you want smart original games that are fun and not generic. Because in the end, it all comes down to the bottom-line for these companies and if you buy the good and none of the generic crap, they will listen and will be happy in gamer land. <br>Roshi out.<br>P.S. since no one posts when I start a discussion, I will leave it open topic.<br><br>&nbsp;<br>current Doac Player;<br>Former eq player.</td></tr>
