	   <tr><td colspan=2>Erm...<br><br>What in the name of sanity is a 'chessie tactic'?  Or a 'chessy tactic', come to that?  Looks sorta like you haven't decided how to spell your new word.  (I'll assume you're not hugely confused and making a reference to chess.  That would imply tactics and strategy.  You're not THAT confused, right?)<br><br>====================================================================<br><i>"I am not dissing EQ itself, i am dissing VERANT INTERACTIVE"<br>"Remember A mmorpg reflects who makes it"<br></i><br>====================================================================<br><br>Everquest and Verant are necessarilly one and the same.  Any product will reflect it's producer's abilities, aims and values.  You can't really aim a complaint at one, or the other, without including it's counterpart.  (Think of it like criticising a child.  The child's behaviour is shaped by it's parents actions and inactions.  You can't say a child is good, or bad, without that being a reflection of the child's parent.  And, conversly, the upbringing supplied by the parent is reflected in the child's behaviour.  Verant is the parent and Everquest is the child.)<br><br>Frankly, I am inclined to think that Everquest has been in need of some serious competition.  A monopoly is never good for it's consumers.  None-the-less, something like one hundred thousand people see fit to pay for the service every month.  No-one forces them to do so.  This would indicate that Everquest is a very good product.<br><br>Take myself as an example:<br>I would normally buy a computer game every four to six weeks.  This would cost me around £30.00.  (This is about $45.00, for those of you who use play money!  *Grin*)  Since I have been playing Everquest, I have bought two games.  Both of these sat in their cellophane wrapping for about two months.  Therefore, it must been seen that I am getting better value from Everquest, than from the games I would normally be buying.  Furthermore, if you consider the numbers for a few moments, you will notice it's also cheaper for me, than my usual spending habits.  Do you see that this is an indicator of high quality?<br><br>This is not to say that I am of the opinion that there is no room for improvement.  I have my own set of gripes about the game and I know they are not unique.  It is my hope that as more competition for my money emerges, these will be resolved.  This of course is why free competition is advantageous for consumers, compared to monopolies.<br><br>With regard to 'project M', I fail to see what your problem is.  <b>Many</b> players are having great fun looking at the world of Norrath from another point of view.  Your argument seems to boil down to not wanting to play any monster that is nigh indestructable.  <i>"I don't wanna be a rat!  I wanna be Vulak'Aaer!  Mommy, tell them I wanna be Vulak'Aaer!!!</i>  I'm pretty sure you wouldn't appreciate this, if you were going to be in a guild raiding this area.  (What happens when you attack another dragon and get yourself killed?  Would it seem right that you wipe out that week's spawn?)<br><br>Project M, for all that it has a stupid name, seems to be both beneficial to players and very successful.  This being the case, both the quality of the service received by the consumer and the probability of continued consumer loyalty is improved.  (And those people who don't like it have lost precisely the square root of f-all.)  Perhaps this is the application of strategy and tactics that you compared to a chess player.<br><br>Either way, I shall just have to wait for your 'GIANT rant' and see what you have to say.  I shall leave you with two thoughts.  It's possible, they may even help you to articulate your arguments!<br><br><b>i.  The truth is malleable.</b><br>The truth is not a fixed constant.  Far from it.  The truth is what the majority believe.  Think upon this for a few moments and you will realise that what I am saying is unavoidably true.  The vast majority of any individual's understanding of the universe he/she inhabits is based upon belief, not knowledge.  This is significant for one very specific reason.  The quality of the service provided by Verant is not actually determined by what the provide.  It is determined by the way that service is perceived by it's users.  I have read your post in Illia's journal complaining that people have deliberately destroyed your Karma, because they dislike your rants.  You suggest through this statement that you have been wrongfully victimised.  Is it not conceivable that people have judged your posts genuinely and given then the rating they feel is correct?  Is it not feasible that the quality of your posts is not in what you think, or have written, but in how other people have perceived this?  If ninety-nine people in one hundred believe what you wrote is trash, then the opinion of the mass states it is trash.  And <b>THAT</b> therefore <b>IS</b> the truth.  But, if it makes you feel better, many great men have been persecuted for their beliefs.  Consider Copernicus in this light.  Perhaps you are an equally great (and misunderstood) genius.<br><br><b>ii. Words are important.</b>    <br>Words frame the way we think.  It is important to use the right words, in the right places.  Otherwise, what you say has no meaning.  And if it has no meaning, you might as well have never spoken!  I'm sure you will understand what I am driving at, with this statement.<br><br>I will wait avidly, for your 'GIANT rant'.<br><br>AlAaraaf.<br>"That which is without meaning is without worth..."<br>&nbsp;<br>"Te aurdire no possum. Musa sapienum fixa est in aura."</td></tr>
