<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100539701240205></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100539701240205><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=journal.html?user=91720&mid=100539701240205>RE: My take...</a> <a id=fs8 href=journal.html?user=91720&mid=100539701240205#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=49677><span id=Sage>alaaraaf the Puissant</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>93 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sat, Nov 10th 7:56 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.87]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Oh dear...<br><br>You know that asking people for constructive criticism in order to improve your writing is dangerous, don't you?  Unless you're incredibly well balanced and the people giving the criticism are very fair, that's almost certain to get you hurt.  (Consider, if you spend an hour writing a long and detailed post and I reply by saying your spelling and grammar are appalling, it will surely be difficult not to see that as a personal attack.  This happens.)<br><br>Anyhow, I want to address a coupa things you said in the post and then I shall offer you a few hints on writing.  (You may not like them, but I shall have fulfilled your request.  What oracle ever did more?  Unlike the oracle at Delphi, I shall at least be very specific.  *Grin*)<br><br><i>"You are right thruth is in the eye of beholder, but a large population beleved that the earth was flat, but they were wrong."</i>(sic)<br>Actually, they weren't wrong.  They lived on a flat Earth.  I'm going to be a little esoteric here, but stay with me and you'll see how this makes sense.  The point I was originally trying to make was that <b>YOUR</b> reality is not necessarilly highly related to whet is around you.  I'll give you an example:<br>I am a computer science student.  (Software engineering.)  My girlfriend, my mom and even my brother, (who has a degree in computer science,) all greatly respect my understanding of computing 'stuff'.  So much so that what I say is essentially accepted as truth.  If I tell my girlfriend that a computer does a thing in a specific way, what I have told her becomes a part of her reality.  It becomes truth.  I regularly tell her that this acceptance of things on a face value is a poor way to understand the world, but this is what the vast majority of people do.<br>Anyhow, enough of this esoterica.  I think by this point you either understand what I am saying, or you never will.  Either way, it is finished.<br><br><i>""Everquest and Verant are necessarilly one and the same. Any product will reflect it's producer's abilities, aims and values." <br>Yep, correct eq does reflect Verants values and I said that. In fact I can quote it: <br>"Remember A MMORPG reflects who makes it, and frankly what eq is now is reflecting verants chessy tactics." <br>"</i><br>I'm pretty sure I'd actually quoted this remark and I don't believe I took it out of context.  (I can't really be bothered going back to my earlier post.  It's early and my feet are cold!  *Grin*)  The problem is that it sounds like you feel that the product and the producer can be separated.  I suposse theoretically this is feasible.  However, for all practical purposes, this isn't workable.  If I write a program, it is inevitable that it will reflect my values.  This site inevitably reflects Allakhazam's and Illia's values.  The two are inextricably bound together.  <br><br>Anyhow, onto AlAaraaf's writing class...<br><br>With just a little luck, you may find a few bits and pieces that help you here.  If you don't, all it's cost you is a coupla minutes to read.  (And the certain knowledge that you're responsible for my getting frostbite!)<br><br><b>Spelling:</b><br>This is a big deal.  Possibly bigger than you realise.  Poor spelling will not often prevent you conveying a message.  It is inevitable that from time to time, everyone will make the occaisional typographical error.  (I have noticed that I type very poorly, when my fingers are cold.  I will then screw up about one word in five.  But, happilly, today my fingers are fine.  Since I'm not typing with my toes, everyone is saved from terrible spelling!)  The effect of poor spelling is that it makes it harder to read what you have to say.  Since you are already writing something that many people don't really want to hear, you do not ideally want to irritate them further.  If you can give the reader a precise view of what you are trying to say, quickly and simply, they will consider your opinion on a far more balanced basis.  Remember, you can always type your rant in a word processor and then copy and paste into the text box.  If you're going to spend hours creating a post, is this not worth considering?<br><br><b>Grammar:</b><br>The importance of grammar is for the same reasons as spelling.  Poor grammar won't often stunt your meaning.  Although it can and this is more likely than with poor spelling.  Consider this:<br><i>"However when I get critizim, it more like your trash for posting that eq sucks."</i><br>When I first read this, I read:<br>"When I get criticism it's more like the trash you (me) posted, because I said EQ sucks."<br>The lack of grammar makes this a little difficult to soak in quickly.  a few tiny changes in the grammar and it would have been much clearer:<br>"However when I get critizim, it<b>{'s}</b> more like<b>{, "}</b> your trash for posting that eq sucks.<b>{"}</b>  "<br>Regardless of this, a few real simple tips for using grammar:<br>Read your text out loud.<br>*  Where there is a natural pause, you want a comma.<br>*  Where there is a natural break, you want a full stop.  <br><i>(Use a comma where the same statement is continuing.  A fullstop where the statement is complete.  (Example:  I like cats, because they are fluffy.  There is a natural pause, at the comma, but because I am continuing with the same statement, I do not use a full stop.  At the end of the sentence, I have completed my statement.  It is terminated and I move on.))</i><br>*  Can you read the whole sentence without having to stop and gulp in air?  If not, it is too long.  Can you break it into smaller pieces?  Several short sentences are easier to read than fewer longer sentences.  This is the case even when the content and the words used are identical.  Use short sentences.  It will make your readers life easier.  (And, if you can make them love you, they're more likely to consider your point of view fairly.)<br><br><b>Justify yourself:</b><br>Above I made the statement that the world WAS flat.  Without some following explanation, such a statement, very few people are going to value what I said.  Likewise, you are telling people who see fit to pay for Everquest that what they are paying for is a bad product.  Unless you justify this claim, what you have said is both without meaning and likely to make people dislike you.  Remember, your Karma is not just the value of your posts.  Won't it effect how somne considers a post if they are thinking: 'Oh look, it's that Roshi guy.  He's such an idiot.'  The value of your post is altered by this.  On the other hand, if someone is thinking happy thoughts, they're likely to appreciate it more:   'Hey, Roshi posted again.  I have to read this, he always has something useful to say!'  (<i>In all honesty, I think you'll find that this is probably the main reason your Karma is ebbing away.  Pre-determined choice is very hard to change.  Think about this!</i>)<br><br><b>Think before you write:</b><br>My lecturers are constantly telling me I should be spending ages planning software on paper, before I touch the keyboard.  There is quite a lot of truth to this.  It's a lot like writing a web page.  You can spot a page that has been written as you go along a mile away.  On the other hand, if the page has been planned before it was written, it has an entirely different feel.<br>This is important whenever you want to present information.  If you work out what you want to say and how to present it, it is likely to work out better.  You <b>can</b> just write stuff and try to correct it later.  However, it is always the case that if you do this, it will take more effort than initial planning would.<br>(Go look at the post on petitions in my journal.  (All of you!  Go to my journal!  Why are you reading 'Roshi's rants', when you could be there?  Go now!  *Grin*)  When I originally wrote this, I did so very quickly and in a single attempt.  When I rewrote it for my journal I had the time to expand areas I felt needed more explanation.  Ultimately, it ended up being a better post for this.  A little planning is worthwhile.  Try it and see.)<br><br><b>UBB code:</b><br>This is justa small bonus really.  But, I am finding it a useful addition.  (Sadly, I can't find the page with the commands.)  UBB code works kinda like HTML tags.  If you've every used HTML you'll find this real easy.  (You just use a square bracket, rather than triangular brackets!)  The tags I have used in this post are:<br><b>Bold:</b> [ b ] Text here [ / b ]<br><i>Italicise:</i> [ i ] Text here [ / i ]<br><i>(Don't have any spaces between the parts of the tag.  I just did it, so you could see how to use it!)</i><br>You can look up the others and play with them, but personally, I find these very useful to bring attention to specific points or words.<br><br>Anyhow, I hope some of this helps.<br><br>AlAaraaf.<br>"Death is coming..."<br><br><br><i>PS:  You'll no doubt all be happy to know that I took a break while writing this and after liberal application of socks and heating, my feet are now cozy.  Just thought I'd let you know, to prevent unnecessary worry.</i><br>&nbsp;<br>"Te aurdire no possum. Musa sapienum fixa est in aura."</td></tr>
